SEKU's new campus in
Makueni county expects to have its first intake in September next year. The Wote campus is the second by South Eastern Kenya University after the one in Mtito Andei.  "We expect to finish construction by next
year," vice chancellor Geoffrey Muluvi said during an inspection of the location on Wednesday. The professor said the campus will offer courses in governance and devolution. "According to our market survey and requests by locals, we will also offer programmes including arid land management, education and law," he said. "We will add what residents suggest along the way." The VC noted government officials will take short courses at the institution that will accommodate 1,500.  